In August 1971 the first public talks on the religion in [[Gaborone]] were undertaken and was broadcast over [[List_of_radio_stations_in_Africa#.C2.A0Botswana|Radio Botswana]] on the topic of "African Traditional Beliefs and the Unity of the World Religions".<ref name="BN492a"/> A review of the community then noted that the national assembly and five local assemblies had incorporated and registered with the government. The national assembly then became legal owners of the national Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> center. Sixty-seven localities had been introduced to the religion and translations of some Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> scripture had been accomplished. Some forty chiefs at various levels had been sent messages by the national assembly about the religion. Fifty-seven villages had been visited with mass meetings resulting. There were only four pioneers present then. The village of Boneapitse was noted as being a majority of Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>s.

An all-Bushman local assembly was first elected in [[Tshasane]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Bushman Assembly| journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1974 | month = February |page = 6 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=584| issue = 492|issn=0195-9212}}</ref> When it was re-elected in 1973 its members were: <nowiki>Ci-!Gau, !'ea, Titi, Diolo, Kaka, Mashipa, N!!g''ae-!Nobo, Baberi, Mpalo.</nowiki>

[[File:LocationKalahari.PNG|thumbnail|The [[Kalahari Desert]] (shown in maroon) & Kalahari Basin (orange)]]

The first national summer school happened Dec 29 to Jan 4 1979-1980 and was followed by a regional conference on the promulgation on the religion with participation of [[Lobatse]], [[Jwaneng]], and [[Kanye, Botswana|Kanye]] in addition to members of the national assembly and auxiliary board members in February.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Bushman Assembly| journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1980| month = September |page = 12 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=260| issue = 594| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> In August 1981 Botswana's first international conference was attended by 150 adults and children from seven countries.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1981 | month = February |page = 14 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=357| issue = 599| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>

In 1984 the Bah<U+00E1>'is of Gaborone held a few public meetings - one highlighted [[UN Day]] at which several city officials attended, another was with visiting counselor Hooper Dunbar which was also covered by television and radio news.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1985 | month = February | page = 15 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=334| issue = 647| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> In 1985 the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>s were invited to a seminar on religions at the University of Batswana.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News| year = 1985 | month = September | page = 15 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=473| issue = 654| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> More than 100 youth met for an international youth conference in August that was opened by the then vice-president of Botswana - [[Peter Mmusi]].<ref>{{cite journal | title = Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News| year = 1985 | month = December | page = 14 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=525| issue = 657| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> That year was also the one when the Universal House of Justice's [[The Promise of World Peace]] was delivered to Bostwana's then president, [[Quett Masire]]<ref>{{cite journal | title = Governments receive peace statement | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1986 | month = February |page = 14 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=565| issue = 659| issn=0195-9212}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = The Promise of World Peace | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News| year = 1988 | month = February |page = 2<U+2013>3 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=228| issue = 683| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>as well as translated in Tswana<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Promise of World Peace | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News| year = 1987 |month = June |page = 12 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=89| issue = 675| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> as part of the overall observance of the UN's [[International Year of Peace]].<ref>{{cite journal | title = International Year of Peace (roll call of nations) - Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News| year = 1987 | month = September |page = 3 |url = http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=136| issue = 678| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> A survey of international standings of the religion in 1987 found that while Bostwana had national and local assemblies recognized legally the [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Holy Days]], marriages and tax exemption as a religion were not recognized.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Statistical Update - Worldwide recognition of the Faith | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News|year = 1987 | month = July |page = 11 |url = http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=106 | issue = 676| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>

===Visits of Hands of the Cause===

[[Hands of the Cause]] are a select group of Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>s, appointed for life, whose main function was to propagate and protect the religion. In May 1972 [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Adelbert M<U+00FC>hlschlegel]] was the first to tour Botswana.<ref name="BN492b">{{cite journal |title = Hand of Cause visits Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1972 | month = March |page = 12-13 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=36| issue = 683| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>

In November 1972 [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Enoch Olinga]] toured the country and visited three of the then newest and most active Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> communities in Botswana - [[Ratholo]] and [[Bonwapitse]] (both in the [[Tswapong Hills]] area), and Palla Road (aka [[Dinokwe]]) He reviewed understanding the religion in a non-literalist way, elaborated on the principals of the religion like of [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith and the unity of humanity|unity of humanity]], [[Progressive revelation (Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>)|progressive revelation]], and that the religion was present in many countries beyond their lands despite the fact that school books did not mention the religion. Later he gave a public talk entitled "The Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith and the Social Order" and a radio interview in [[Gaborone]] where he addressed wide ranging topics from the definition of the word "Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>", the [[History of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith|history of the religion]], its relationship with [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith and the unity of religion|Christianity]] and the difficulties with social norms in [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith in South Africa|South Africa]].

In June 1973 Hand of the Cause [[Ruhiyyih Khanum]] toured the country for some 20 days.<ref>{{cite journal |title = The Great Safari of Hand of the Cause Ruhiyyih Khanum, part 15  | last = Nakhjavani | first = Violette | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1973 | month = April |page = 16-21 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=351| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> She was met an hour's walk from the village of [[Selebi-Phikwe]] by a new mother with a week old baby. At a few villages including [[Seleka]] she met with local school teachers. She congratulated the pioneers that were well out in the countryside rather than clustered in the capital. At another village she spoke at a teacher's training college noting the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teaching of [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith and gender equality|equality of the sexes]] and the importance of mothers and teachers, [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith and education|eliminating illiteracy]] but that matters of faith are not dependent on book learning. In [[Bonwapitse]] she addressed the importance of prayer, the meaning of "[[All<U+00E1>h'u'Abh<U+00E1>]]". In [[Mmutlane]] she addressed the topic of dreams related about [[Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h]] and the [[B<U+00E1>b]]. She went on to other villages and illustrated diverse responses to faith. In the [[Kalahari Desert]] she met with Bushmen when only a few had joined the religion so far hoping the religion would help preserve their qualities of gentleness and goodness. Then she met with the national assembly especially about the topic of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> view of "consultation", that the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> funds are to be spent on specific purposes for the promulgation of the religion. At [[Lobatse]] she spoke at another teacher's training college on the importance of youth. The final village was [[Sub-districts_of_Botswana#Southern_District|Good Hope]] where she met the first Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>s of Botswana -Mr. and Mrs. Moncho.

In March 1978 Hand of the Cause [[Collis Featherstone|H. Collis Featherstone]] toured Botswana for a week speaking of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> views on themes of the religion and presented an address on radio.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Botswana: Hand of the Cause visits  |journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1978 | month = September |page = 13 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=815| issue = 570| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> In April [[John Robarts (Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>)|John Robarts]], who was appointed a Hand of the Cause in 1957, and his wife Audrey returned to Botswana. They visited several villages and old friends and were interviewed in the [[Media of Botswana|Botswana Daily News]] and Radio Botswana.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Botswana  | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1981 |month = December |page = 14 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=556| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>

===Individual stories===
Paula Rath lived in Botswana in 1972-73 with her former husband, Dick Graham as Baha<U+2019>i pioneers and ran a little newspaper called Puisano.<Ref>{{cite web
| last =Rath
 | first = Paula
 | title =Titi, my Bushman Friend in Botswana
