Lally Warren was a member of the [[Institution of the Counsellors|Continental Board of Counsellors]] in Africa from 1985 to 2000 and has served the religion in many other capacities.<ref name="Golden"/>

===Sustained women's groups===

In 1975 a pair of women from Rhodesia traveled a few places in the country holding extended classes on the religion in a few locations advancing the activity of women. The pair were joined by a few local youth.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Botswana  |journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1975 | month = December |page = 18-19 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=157| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> Indeed in 1976 five handicraft clubs for Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> women were functioning with the assistance of Iran Sohaili from Rhodesia.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Clubs for Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> women organized  | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1976 | month = December |page = 2 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=406| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> There was a continued meeting in 1978 when a small group of Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>s visited them for a week and were encouraged them to adopt an extension goal of a nearby village.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Botswana: Deepening institute held| journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1979 | month = May |page = 14 |url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=738| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>

== Modern community ==

Since its inception the religion has had involvement in [[socio-economic development]] beginning by giving greater freedom to women,<ref name="iranhistory">{{cite web | last = Momen | first = Moojan | title = History of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith in Iran | work = draft "A Short Encyclopedia of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith" | publisher = Bahai-library.com | date = | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_encyclopedia_iran#9.%20Social%20and%20economic%20development  |accessdate = 2009-10-16}}</ref> promulgating the promotion of female education as a priority concern,<ref>{{cite journal |last = Kingdon | first = Geeta Gandhi | title = Education of women and socio-economic development | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Studies Review | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | year = 1997 | url =http://bahai-library.com/kingdon_education_women_development |postscript = . }}</ref> and that involvement was given practical expression by creating schools, agricultural coops, and clinics.<ref name="iranhistory" /> The religion entered a new phase of activity when a message of the [[Universal House of Justice]] dated 20 October 1983 was released.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith 1957<U+2013>1988: A Survey of Contemporary Developments | first = Moojan | last = Momen | coauthors = Smith, Peter | year = 1989 | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_smith_developments_1957-1988 |volume = 19 | journal = Religion |issue=1 | pages=63<U+2013>91|doi=10.1016/0048-721X(89)90077-8 |postscript=.}}</ref> Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>s were urged to seek out ways, compatible with the [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teachings]], in which they could become involved in the social and economic development of the communities in which they lived. World-wide in 1979 there were 129 officially recognized Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> socio-economic development projects. By 1987, the number of officially recognized development projects had increased to 1482. 

===Youth projects===
Among the earliest development projects in Botswana was a systematic initiation of a major "Youth Year of Service" project which coordinated volunteer activities with assemblies with a defined need.<ref>{{cite journal |title = A look at programs around the world| journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1988 | month = April |page = 2<U+2013>3|url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=265| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> This was extended by an orientation program of youth in diverse traditional African cultures.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Botswana | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1988 | month = December |page = 15|url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=431| issue = 505| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> Meanwhile recognition of the work of the national government in support of human rights was presented by the national assembly - at the reception ambassadors and diplomatic core from several countries and the UN. The UN representative invited the Baha'is in turn to co-sponso the 1988 UN Day observance. An international youth conference was held in 1989 at which 120 people from 13 countries attended.<ref>{{cite journal |title = Botswana| journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1990 | month = February |page = 14|url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=693| issue = 706| issn=0195-9212}}</ref> In December youth from [[Transkei]] were among the choirs that performed at a Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International Music Festival in Botswana.<ref>{{cite journal |title = A Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> choir from... | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> News | year = 1990 | month = March |page = 16|url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=12&page=714| issue = 706| issn=0195-9212}}</ref>

During 1994-95, youth camps were particularly popular in Botswana where the community held the country's first youth camp. For one week, youth gathered at the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Institute in [[Mahalapye]] and studied the life of [[Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h]], the [[Kitab-i-Aqdas]], and such teachings of the religion as [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> marriage|chastity and marriage]], and the [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith on life after death|immortality of the soul]].<ref>{{cite web
| title =Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Youth: "A New Kind of People"
 | work =
 | publisher =Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International Community
 | year = 2013
 | url =http://info.bahai.org/article-1-9-2-8.html}}</ref>

"Who is Writing the Future? A Seminar on the Issues of the 21st Century<U+201D> in 2000 held on the campus of the [[University of Botswana]].<ref>{{cite web
| title =Invitation and Program
 | work =
 | publisher =Association for Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Studies in Southern Africa
 | date =March 2, 2000
 | url =http://bci.org/bahaistudies/seminars/seminar-ub-invite.htm }}</ref>

===Broader efforts===

In 2001 then President of Botswana [[Festus Mogae]] praised publication of Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> books in native [[Setswana language]].<ref>{{cite news
| title =President of Botswana praises publication of Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> books in native Setswana language
 | newspaper =Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> World News Service
 | publisher =Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International Community
 | date =27 February 2001
 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/130
 | accessdate = July 12, 2013}}</ref> One was a book of [[Prayer in the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith|Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> prayers]] in its third reprint with a revised translation and the other was the [[The Hidden Words]] of Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h (published as "Mafoko a a Subilweng a ga Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h".) The book of prayers<ref name="bookofprayers" /> is available online for free.<ref>{{cite web
| title =Dithapelo Tsa Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>, tse di senotsweng ke Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h, B<U+00E1>b, le 'Abdu'l-Bah<U+00E1>
 | work =Baha'i Prayers
 | publisher =Lekgotla la Semowa la Sechaba la Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> ba Botswana
 | year =1999
 | url =http://bahaiprayers.org/setswana/ }} , see also {{cite web
| last =uploaded by Massoud Derakhshani
 | first =
 | title =Setswana Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Prayer
 | date =Jun 12, 2009
 | url =http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yOAxWtpnPNI
 | accessdate = July 12, 2013 }}</ref>

The minister of local government of Botswana, Margaret Nasha, commended the activities of the community when she addressed its golden jubilee held December 2004.<ref name="Golden"/>

Bah<U+00E1><U+2019><U+00ED>s from Botswana were among the thousand who gathered for a regional conference called for by the [[Universal House of Justice]] to be held in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, in November 2008.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International Community |first = | author-link = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International Community | title = The Johannesburg Regional Conference | newspaper = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International News Service | pages = |date = 2008-11-23 | url = http://news.bahai.org/community-news/regional-conferences/johannesburg.html | postscript = .}}</ref> 

===Individuals===
Robert Sylvester grew up Catholic in the United States but converted to the religion in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite episode
| title = Robert Sylvester
| episodelink =
| url = http://www.bahaipodcast.com/archives.asp?pYrID=2008
| series = A Baha'i Perspective
| serieslink = http://www.bahaipodcast.com/default.asp
| credits = Warren Odess-Gillett
| network = Valley Free Radio
| airdate = July 21, 2008
| season = 2008
| seriesno =
| number =
| minutes = }}</ref> He and his wife moved to Zambia in the later 1970s where he worked in a school and served in the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> community there. Then they moved to Botswana. He would serve as Principal (Chief Executive Officer) of [[Westwood International School]] in [[Gaborone]], Botswana from 1990 to 2000. During the same period he also served in some institutions of the religion-appointed to the Permanent Bah<U+00E1><U+2019><U+00ED> Training Institute in Botswana on its Board of Directors (1996-2000) and as External Affairs Officer for the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah<U+00E1><U+2019><U+00ED>s of Botswana (1999-2000) and then moved back to the United States.<ref>{{cite web
| last = Sylvester
 | first = Robert F.
 | title = Vita of Robert F. Sylvester
 | url = http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:m5_T0Z0NcPUJ:webhost.bridgew.edu/rsylvester/bahai.rtf&cd=10&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us }}</ref>

Shahin Lockman and her husband served a number of medical posts including in Botswana.<ref>{{cite web
 | title =Drs. Roger Shapiro and Shahin Lockman - Partners in Research & Parenting
 | work =News & Publications, Spotlight newsletter | publisher =HAI - Harvard School of Public Health AIDS Initiative
 | date =Fall 2010
 | url =http://www.aids.harvard.edu/news/spotlight/archives/v7i3_shapiro_lockman_profile.html}}</ref> Lockman worked on tuberculosis in Botswana. On her first visit there in 1996, another disease caught her attention: HIV/AIDS. Both eventually worked in the first clinical trial of the [[Botswana-Harvard AIDS Institute]] partnership in 2000.

Sean Hinton, a member of the [[Aspen Institute]]'s Leaders Action Forum, served as the supporter and catalyst for an HIV/AIDS awareness project called Letsema la Itlotlo (conceived by his parents-in-law Gerald and Lally Warren) to promote change in the behaviors that lead to the spread of HIV/AIDS in Botswana by using traditional cultural teachings and the values associated with religious belief as forces of attitudinal change.<ref>{{cite web
| title =About Sean Hinton
 | work =Action Forum Participants
 | publisher =The Aspen Institute
 | date =August 1, 2013
 | url =http://www.aspenleadersactionforum.org/user/149}}</ref> Two founding grants were received from De Beers Botswana and from the Office of Social and Economic Development of the [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> International Community]].

In 2009 Lucretia Warren, chairperson of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah<U+00E1><U+2019><U+00ED>s of Botswana and a former member of the Bah<U+00E1><U+2019><U+00ED> Continental Board of Counsellors for Africa,<ref>{{cite journal
